com.bluegosling.collections.concurrent

Class SimpleTreiberStack<T>

  • java.lang.Object
    • java.util.AbstractCollection<T>
      • com.bluegosling.collections.concurrent.SimpleTreiberStack<T>
  • Type Parameters:
    T - the type of values stored in the stack
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    ConcurrentStack<T>, Stack<T>, Iterable<T>, Collection<T>

    public class SimpleTreiberStack<T>
extends AbstractCollection<T>
implements ConcurrentStack<T>
    A very simple, thread-safe stack. This is a simpler and lighter weight version than TreiberStack. It does not support arbitrary remove operations, only pop(). All operations are atomic.

    This structure is safe to use concurrently from multiple threads. The iterator will never throw a ConcurrentModificationException. However, each single iterator is meant to be used from a single thread and is thus not thread safe. Iterators do not support the Iterator.remove() operation. Iterators are strongly consistent, yielding elements in the stack at the time the iterator was created.

    See Also:
    TreiberStack

      • drainTo

        public void drainTo(Collection<? super T> coll)
        Description copied from interface: ConcurrentStack
        Atomically drains the stack by popping all elements from the stack and adding them to the given collection. The top of the stack will be the first item added to the collection.

        If the given collection is thread-safe and published to multiple threads, the additions of elements may not appear atomic.

        Specified by:
        drainTo in interface ConcurrentStack<T>
        Parameters:
        coll - the collection into which items are drained
